        "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/questions/35602543/xml-attribute-in-java",
        "last_activity_date": 1456320205,
        "creation_date": 1456317771,
        "answer_count": 1,
        "title": "XML Attribute In Java",
        "body": "<pre><code>&lt;xs:element type=\"xs:string\" name=\"TheMainElement\" maxOccurs=\"unbounded\"&gt;\n    &lt;xs:complexType&gt;\n        &lt;xs:attribute type=\"xs:string\" name=\"Attribute1OrAttribute2\"&gt;\n        &lt;/xs:attribute&gt;\n    &lt;/xs:complexType&gt;\n&lt;/xs:element&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>I have the created the above XSD for an output of the following XML:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>&lt;TheMainElement Attribute1OrAttribute2=\"Attribute1\"&gt;Text&lt;/TheMainElement&gt;\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>From the java coding perspective, I understand the element creation and if I attempted the same for the attribute too, it would have an end bracket as that too. <\/p>\n\n<pre><code>Element TheMainElement = document.createElement(\"TheMainElement\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>How can I add the Attribute part without it appearing in the end bracket?<\/p>\n",
        "question_id": 35602543,
        "tags": [
            "java",
            "xml",
            "xsd"
        ],
        "score": 0,
        "accepted_answer_id": 35603143,
        "is_answered": true,
        "view_count": 140
    },
    "question_comments": [],
    "answers": [{
        "owner": {
            "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/1nw4e.jpg?s=256",
            "account_id": 1996476,
            "user_type": "registered",
            "user_id": 1789356,
            "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1789356/zoom",
            "reputation": 1776,
            "display_name": "zoom",
            "accept_rate": 86
        },
        "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
        "score": 0,
        "is_accepted": true,
        "last_activity_date": 1456320205,
        "creation_date": 1456319373,
        "body": "<p>Have a look at <code>org.w3c.dom.Element#setAttribute(String name, String value)<\/code><\/p>\n\n<p>So in your case it would be<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>TheMainElement.setAttribute(\"Attribute1OrAttribute2\", \"Attribute1\");\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>Depending on your needs, you can also have a look at the <code>org.w3c.dom.Element#setAttributeNode(Attr newAttr)<\/code>. You would have to implement the <code>Attr<\/code> interface or use a dedicated library that already provides some implementation such as <a href=\"https://dom4j.github.io/\" rel=\"nofollow\">dom4j<\/a>, which will also help you to create a manipulate XML documents.<\/p>\n\n<p>As a side note, i would personnally discourage the use of variable with the first letter capitalized , the standard would be to use lower camel case <code>TheMainElement -&gt; theMainElement<\/code>\nSee the <a href=\"https://google.github.io/styleguide/javaguide.html#s5.2.7-local-variable-names\" rel=\"nofollow\">google java style guide<\/a> for example<\/p>\n",
        "answer_id": 35603143,
        "question_id": 35602543,
        "last_edit_date": 1456320205
    }],
